Thought for 22s

Got it—here are clean, copy-pasteable ways to move your .jks between Linux servers. I’ll show both paths:

A) Copy via your local machine (remote → local → other remote)

1) Pull from Server A to your laptop:

# From your laptop/desktop
scp -P <PORT_A> -p userA@serverA:/path/to/keystore.jks ./keystore.jks


-P = SSH port (omit if 22)

-p = preserve timestamps/mode

2) Push from your laptop to Server B:

scp -P <PORT_B> -p ./keystore.jks userB@serverB:/path/where/you/want/keystore.jks


If you need a custom key file:

scp -i ~/.ssh/id_rsa -P <PORT> -p source target

B) Copy directly between the two servers (no local save)
Option 1: scp -3 (third-party copy via your machine, but not stored)
# From your laptop/desktop
scp -3 -p \
  -P <PORT_A> userA@serverA:/path/to/keystore.jks \
  -P <PORT_B> userB@serverB:/path/where/you/want/keystore.jks


-3 streams through your client without writing a local file.

Option 2: SSH pipe (works even if rsync isn’t installed)
# From your laptop/desktop
ssh -p <PORT_A> userA@serverA "cat /path/to/keystore.jks" \
  | ssh -p <PORT_B> userB@serverB "cat > /path/where/you/want/keystore.jks"

Option 3: rsync remote→remote (requires rsync on both servers)
# From your laptop/desktop
rsync -av -e "ssh -p <PORT_A>" userA@serverA:/path/to/keystore.jks \
          -e "ssh -p <PORT_B>" userB@serverB:/path/where/you/want/


If only one custom port: put it in the matching -e "ssh -p ..." half.

Use -z to compress if the file is big: rsync -avz ...

If you need sudo on the destination path

You usually can’t write directly to a root-owned dir via scp. Do:

# copy to a writable temp dir
scp -p ./keystore.jks userB@serverB:/tmp/keystore.jks

# then on Server B:
ssh userB@serverB "sudo mv /tmp/keystore.jks /secure/path/keystore.jks && sudo chown appuser:appgroup /secure/path/keystore.jks && sudo chmod 640 /secure/path/keystore.jks"


For rsync with sudo on the remote:

rsync -av ./keystore.jks userB@serverB:/tmp/
ssh userB@serverB "sudo install -m 640 -o appuser -g appgroup /tmp/keystore.jks /secure/path/keystore.jks"

Quick integrity check (optional but nice)

On Server A:

sha256sum /path/to/keystore.jks


On Server B:

sha256sum /path/where/you/wrote/keystore.jks


Compare the hashes—must match.

Tips

Paths with spaces: quote them, e.g. "'/path/with space/keystore.jks'".

Faster over slow links: add -C to scp or -z to rsync.

Identity files: scp -i ~/.ssh/id_ed25519 ...

Preserve times/mode: scp -p (you’ll still set final owner/perm with chown/chmod as needed).

Tell me your exact hostnames/ports and where the file needs to land (and whether you need sudo), and I’ll give you the one-liner tailored to your setup.
